      <hedline>
        <hl1>Scooters and Helmets</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Vicki Richman letter comments on September 27 article on death of six-year-old boy in Elizabeth, NJ, who was struck and killed while using foot-powered scooter to cross street</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A driver in Elizabeth, N.J., struck and killed a 6-year-old using a foot-powered scooter to cross the street (''Boy's Death Leads to Calls for Helmets With Scooters,'' news article, Sept. 27).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A driver in Elizabeth, N.J., struck and killed a 6-year-old using a foot-powered scooter to cross the street (''Boy's Death Leads to Calls for Helmets With Scooters,'' news article, Sept. 27).</p>
        <p>The police agree that a helmet could not have saved the boy's life, and that his use of the scooter had no effect on the events leading to his death.</p>
        <p>What is the response by state legislators? 1. Pass a law requiring scooter riders to wear helmets. 2. Regulate the use of scooters. 3. Say nothing about the use of motor vehicles on public roads.</p>
        <p>The press further describes the death as ''scooter-related,'' not automobile-related. The mind boggles.</p>
        <p>VICKI RICHMAN  New York, Sept. 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
